{"id":"1308.5720","submitter":"Joseph Paulsen","authors":"Joseph D. Paulsen","title":"Approach and Coalescence of Liquid Drops in Air","comments":"15 pages, 16 figures","journal-ref":"Phys. Rev. E 88, 063010 (2013)","doi":"10.1103/PhysRevE.88.063010","report-no":null,"categories":"physics.flu-dyn cond-mat.soft","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  The coalescence of liquid drops has conventionally been thought to have just\ntwo regimes when the drops are brought together slowly in vacuum or air: a\nviscous regime corresponding to the Stokes-flow limit and a later\ninertially-dominated regime. Recent work [Proc. Natl. Acad. Sci. 109, 6857\n(2012)] found that the Stokes-flow limit cannot be reached in the early moments\nof coalescence, because the inertia of the drops cannot be neglected then.\nInstead, the drops are described by an \"inertially limited viscous\" regime,\nwhere surface tension, inertia, and viscous forces all balance. The dynamics\ncontinue in this regime until either viscosity or inertia dominate on their\nown. I use an ultrafast electrical method and high-speed imaging to provide a\ndetailed description of coalescence near the moment of contact for drops that\napproach at low speed and coalesce as undeformed spheres. These measurements\nsupport a description of coalescence having three regimes. Signatures both\nbefore and after contact identify a threshold approach-speed for deformation of\nthe drops by the ambient gas.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Mon, 26 Aug 2013 23:33:27 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Thu, 9 Jan 2014 19:52:15 GMT"}],"update_date":"2014-01-10"}
